issue.title: Fix unixCmd PID management on Windows

labels.name: comp: sclang
labels.description: sclang C++ implementation (primitives, etc.). for changes to class lib use "comp: class library"

issue.body:
<!-- For information about contributing see: https://github.com/supercollider/supercollider/wiki/Contributing-directory -->

## Purpose and Motivation

<!-- Please provide a description, even if you are linking to a related Issue or PR. -->
<!-- If this fixes an open issue, link to it by writing "Fixes #555." -->

Fixes #6742

In this PR:
- `ArrayedCollection -unixCmd` is fixed to _not_ run the command through `cmd.exe`, which matches behavior on *nix
  - as a result, a proper PID of the requested command is now returned from this method
- `Platform -killProcessByID` is changed to kill child processes as well; this enables e.g. [closing an unresponsive server](https://github.com/supercollider/supercollider/blob/develop/SCClassLibrary/Common/Control/Server.sc#L1123), which didn't seem to work before, aside from `Server.killAll`
- `String -unixCmd` still returns the PID of `cmd.exe` and not of the specified command, but there doesn't seem to be a straightforward solution for this (see notes https://github.com/supercollider/supercollider/issues/6742#issuecomment-2869010570), as `execvp` used on *nix for running a command is not available on Windows, IIUC.
- Documentation for the PID behavior was added 


How to test this:
```supercollider
// kill task test
p = unixCmd(Server.program + s.options.asOptionsString, {"I'm done!".postln}); // run scsynth using String -unixCmd
p.postln; // check pid - it is different than the scsynth pid in Task Manager
thisProcess.platform.killProcessByID(p); // scsynth should still exit

// pid with ArrayedCollection
r = [Server.program, "-u", "57110"].unixCmd; // run scsynth using ArrayedCollection -unixCmd
r.postln; // this should match the scsynth pid in Task Manager
thisProcess.platform.killProcessByID(r); // scsynth should exit
```


## Types of changes

<!-- Delete lines that don't apply -->

- Documentation
- Bug fix

## To-do list

<!-- Complete an item by checking it: [x]. Add new entries to track your progress -->

- [x] Code is tested
- [ ] All tests are passing
- [x] Updated documentation
- [x] This PR is ready for review <!-- If not ready for review, consider making a Draft PR instead, or describe what kind of specific feedback you want. -->

<!-- ## Merge notes
(optional) You may also add notes of:
     - Dependencies: if this PR depends on any other PRs or actions
     - Merge Note: any considerations regarding merging this PR
     - Release Notes: text you think would be useful to include in the Release Notes
-->

<!-- Note: The recommended commit message format is:
     component: sub-component: short description of changes
For example:
     classlib: ClassBrowser: fix search with empty query string
Common `comp:` labels:
     help, classlib, sclang, scsynth, plugins, tests, docs, SCDoc
See wiki for more info: Wiki->Creating Pull Requests->git-commit-message-format
-->

comment.body:
> HOWEVER I remember previously seeing a separate sh shell being spun and getting a PID of that!

Yes, that's exactly what I would expect. In fact, I don't really see how `sh -c <command>` could possibly return the PID of `<command>`.

Thanks for the linked issue. I didn't know that `SequenceCollection -unixCmd` was added after `String -unixCmd`. They really should have picked a different name :)

pull_request.title: Make things build on Linux
pull_request.body:
This PR implements enough of the Windows APIs that it's possible to build Lego Island on Linux (x86_64).

```bash
cmake -S . -B build
cmake --build build -j 32
```

The current implementations are just empty stubs. They mostly assume everything went well, yet just return null pointers when asked to create or fetch something.

This is enough that the application is able to boot, read the config, create a window (full screen or windowed), and then detect that "DirectDraw" find suitable hardware to run no-ops on.

![image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a26036ad-e4f3-4910-a1b4-d31f8ee1d25b)

The configuration application also builds, though it fails much earlier since it doesn't have any code for creating a window and just gives up after that.

How ever both applications shut down nicely so there are no noticeable bugs just missing features :)

The next step would probably be for someone to go in and implement some of the most obviously missing functions and add `assert(false)` to all renaming functions, then iterate until everything works.

To help with the process I also added ASAN and a CI build script. Have fun building :)

P.s. this in no way aims to be a proper implementation of any of the APIs and instead is just what is needed to be source compatible from Lego Islands perspective, lots of enum values and relations are just made up on the fly and not the values used in the real APIs but I considered that out of scope.

P.s.s. if it was me implementing the replacement render I would start by moving all methods to the non-versioned classes and making the versioned empty extensions that should make it look like more of an asset loading API and making implementing the render engine more straight forward.

issue.title: [4.3] Android 14: Export Template with changed minSdk results in pre-align errors
issue.body:
### Tested versions

- Reproducible in 4.3.stable and 4.2.2.stable

### System information

Godot v4.3.stable - Linux Mint 21.3 (Virginia) - X11 - GLES3 (Compatibility)

### Issue description

Since Android 14 has an hard requirement for the minSdk version to be 23, I've compiled an export template where I've changed `platform/android/java/app/config.gradle`'s minSdk directly and compiled the export templates as such with both arm32 and arm64.

After trying to export the game **without** `Gradle Build` option, the resulting APK is not installable on my Android 14 device. The export settings are the following:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/e3eca188-5f06-4e32-90c8-caf8bccebed6)

The error on `adb install` can be seen below:
```
Performing Incremental Install
Serving...
Failure [INSTALL_FAILED_INTERNAL_ERROR: INSTALL_FAILED_INTERNAL_ERROR: Failed to extract native libraries, res=-110]
Performing Streamed Install
adb: failed to install test.apk: Failure [INSTALL_FAILED_INVALID_APK: INSTALL_FAILED_INVALID_APK: Failed to extract native libraries, res=-2]
```

With the following logcat error:
```
PackageInstallerSession: START COMMIT SESSION: id{112768871}
NativeLibraryHelper: Library 'libgodot_android.so' is not page-aligned - will not be able to open it directly from apk.
NativeHelper: Failure copying native libraries [errorCode=-2]
PackageInstallerSession: Marking session 112768871 as failed: INSTALL_FAILED_INVALID_APK: Failed to extract native libraries, res=-2
PackageInstallerSession: Failed to verify session 112768871
PackageInstallerSession: result of session: -2{112768871}, INSTALL_FAILED_INVALID_APK: Failed to extract native libraries, res=-2
```

After looking around the issues I found a similar problem reported for Godot 3.2.4 in issue #42792, which took me to the `zipalign` and allowed me to check the resulting APK with `zipalign` and re-align it. This however revokes the signature and you will have to sign it again afterwards.

For now the workaround is to pre-align the libs and re-sign with:
```
# Export APK in Godot
zipalign -p -f 4 test.apk test-aligned.apk
apksigner sign --ks ... --ks-pass ... --ks-key-alias ... test-aligned.apk
```

EDIT:
~~Need to confirm before being sure, but for Android 14, the alignment might be required to be 8 bytes instead of 4 bytes, which would result in the zipalign command being `zipalign -p -f 8 test.apk test-aligned.apk` instead.~~
Seems to not be necessary after all.

### Steps to reproduce

1. Compile an export template for Android with an higher minSdk on `platform/android/java/app/config.gradle` and both arm32 and arm64
2. Export a game for Android **without** Gradle Build, using that compiled export
3. Attempt to install the resulting game in an Android 14 device

### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

N/A
